As has been seen, the removal of N−H proton of 2-MeHIm has led to dramatic changes in both geometric and electronic structures of Co(II) porphyrinates. The changes appear unexpected because the imidazolate has been accepted as a strong ligand, which would induce LS species, e.g., in the alkaline transition5–7. Thus, we have conducted DFT calculations to investigate the products’ electronic configurations (Supplementary Figs. 22–25 and Supplementary Data 1). M06/6-31G(d)/TZVP level of theory has predicted 2.6 and 5.7 kcal/mol more stable LS [Co(TPP)(2-MeHIm)] and HS [Co(TPP)(2-MeIm−)]−, respectively, in agreement with the experimental results. Qualitative diagrams showing the d-orbital energy ordering are illustrated in Fig. 5. The MOs of low and high-spin [Co(TPP)(2-MeIm−)]− are compared in Fig. 5b. The dramatically lowered \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
